data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>`, which checks the type **and** returns the typed instance:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives you a clearer failure message (expected vs actual type) instead of an `InvalidCastException`, and eliminates the null check since the assertion itself fails if the type doesn't match.

> **Note:** The generic overload that returns the typed value was added in **MSTest v3.3**. On older versions, use the non-generic form, but you'll still need a cast afterward:
> ```csharp
> Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
> ```
